04541nam a22006375i 9781501737350DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20191994nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017373507 a10.7591/97815017373502doi  a(DE-B1597)545748  a(OCoLC)1198930635  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0230002bisacsh1 aNowell, Gregory P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMercantile States and the World Oil Cartel, 1900-1939 /cGregory P. Nowell. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b4 drawings, 4 maps, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Transnational Structuring and the World Order -- t2. Transnational Structuring before World War I: The Pattern of State Monopoly Attempts and Market Interventions -- t3. The Great War and the Struggle for Commercial Advantage, 1914-1921 -- t4. France and the Development of the World Oil Cartel, 1922-1939 -- t5. The World Hydrocarbon Cartel, 1922-1939 -- t6. Conclusion: Transnational Structuring and the World Order -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early twentieth century, the pattern of industrial energy consumption began its massive shift from reliance on coal to dependence on oil. This seismic event changed the world's strategic geography, overturned established relations between business and state, and resulted in global dominance for a select group of powerful oil multinationals. Providing a definitive history of these events, Gregory P. Nowell calls into question some common assumptions about the relations between international corporate struggles and national policymaking in such "mercantile" states as France.Nowell reveals how the men who organized the world oil cartel of 1928 maintained a coherent strategy of transnational regulation as they controlled new hydrocarbon technologies through elaborate patent agreements. The cartel's strategy, Nowell argues, became the common fabric from which individual states cut their national oil policies, among them such apparently diverse measures as the French oil import law of 1928, the Red Line agreement controlling Iraqi oil exports, and the Texas Railroad Commission. Focusing on France, the author examines policy decisions aimed at safeguarding longterm supplies of petroleum, including adjudication of conflicts between Standard Oil and rival European companies. Drawing on extensive primary sources in France and the United States, Nowell details the processes through which the cartel's transnational structuring shaped the energy goals of France and of other nations, guided these nations' institutional development, and helped determine the international distribution of market power and technology. His analysis of the broad sweep of world oil politics leads to a penetrating critique of major theories of international relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 4aGeneral Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173735040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501737350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501737350.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK